Head − Anterior ⅔ of labium dark brown, posterior third yellow-brown. Rear of head of normal shape. Labrum and clypeus shining metallic black. Genae and mandibles dull yellow with the latter black in the upper anterior corner; remainder of head including antennae dull black (
Fig. 13
).

Thorax − Sides of prothorax and middle lobe of pronotum covered with dark blue pruinosity. Anterior and posterior lobe of pronotum black. Posterior lobe of pronotum broad, largely flat but with the outer border raised, lateral corners rounded. Pattern of thorax largely obscured by blue pruinosity (
Fig. 21
).

This species shows, like 

C. cinctus

, small regional variability in the shape of the inferior appendages. This variability was deemed too small to warrant any taxonomical status. The amount of black on head thorax and legs shows not only variability due to age but shows also regional variability with specimens of northern populations having a less extensive black pattern. This variability is gradual and does not allow the recognition of subspecies. Head − In specimens of the northern population the pale markings are more extensive running up along the eyes and to the sockets of the antennae and covering the outer corners of the postclypeus (
Fig. 14
). In specimens from the South the pattern on the head is as in the holotype (
Fig. 13
). Thorax − In specimens of southern populations the front on the thorax is almost completely black (
Fig. 21
), whereas in specimens of northern populations a large yellow-brown stripe is present on both sides of it (
Fig. 22
). Legs − Specimens of southern populations have legs like the holotype: femora brown with extensive black near knees and black keel; tibiae and tarsi brown. In specimens of the northern populations the black on the legs is slightly less extensive but they have two broad but faint black rings on the femur.
